The paper discusses the use of crowdsourcing for policymaking, which involves aspects of computer science, social science, and political science. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CY (Computers and Society), which deals with the intersection of computer science and social issues. The paper also discusses the use of technology for collaboration and decision-making, which falls under the categories of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.CSCW (Computer-Supported Cooperative Work). Additionally, the paper discusses the role of crowdsourcing in shaping policy, which falls under the categories of cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks) and cs.POL (Computational Social Science and Government).
